question.title: How to display HashSet objects in preserve order?

node.contents: Basically HashSet following insertion order is not preserved, but I want to display HashSet objects in the form of preserve order in Java.

astNode.text: Basically HashSet following insertion order is not preserved, but I want to display HashSet objects in the form of preserve order in Java.

node.contents: Is it possible? If yes then can you please share some ideas.

astNode.text: Is it possible? If yes then can you please share some ideas.

node.contents: You can use LinkedHashSet, which preserves insertion order.

astNode.text: You can use LinkedHashSet, which preserves insertion order.

node.contents: If the order of insertion is important, maybe you should use an ArrayList.

astNode.text: If the order of insertion is important, maybe you should use an ArrayList.

node.contents: For Set there is LinkedHashSet and for Map there is LinkedHashMap - both retain the order in which items were inserted although there is a very small performance impact.

astNode.text: For Set there is LinkedHashSet and for Map there is LinkedHashMap - both retain the order in which items were inserted although there is a very small performance impact.

node.contents: There is also the option of TreeMap and TreeSet which do not retain the order in which elements were inserted but instead keeps them in a specified order (either their natural ordering or as specified by a comparator).

astNode.text: There is also the option of TreeMap and TreeSet which do not retain the order in which elements were inserted but instead keeps them in a specified order (either their natural ordering or as specified by a comparator).

node.contents: I have already Set, but I want to display that Set in the same order in java. Can you please share a piece of code. Thanks in advance

astNode.text: I have already Set, but I want to display that Set in the same order in java. Can you please share a piece of code. Thanks in advance

node.contents: Use LinkedHashSet it preserves the order of insertion.

astNode.text: Use LinkedHashSet it preserves the order of insertion.

elements.contents: Set<String> set = new LinkedHashSet<String>(); for(int i = 0; i <5; i++) { set.add( i+"" ); } // insertion order is 0,1,2,3,4 for(String str : set) { System.out.println(str); } //output 0,1,2,3,4

node.contents: Use LinkedHashSet instead of HashSet. LinkedHashSet will maintain the insertion order.
